AGI - Scottish Independent Premier Humza Yousaf> resigned to avoid a double vote of distrust in the local parliament, where his party, the SNP, is more in difficulty than ever a year after Nicholas Sturgeon's farewell. The overcoming of the current political divisions "can only be done with someone else at the helm", he said in a press conference from his official residence at the Bute House in Edinburgh.
&nbsp;
Humza Yousaf, 39, was elected leader of the SNP in March 2023, after the surprise resignation of former Prime Minister Nicola Sturgeon after nine years in power. First Muslim leader at the head of an important political party in the United Kingdom, he embodied continuity with his predecessor by supporting the struggle for Scottish independence despite the vacillating popularity of the SNP. The resignations come four days after the collapse of the coalition of government between the Scottish National Party and environmentalists, in full disagreement on the country's environmental policy. Another hot topic was the government's decision to suspend the prescription of puberty blockers > to young transgenders, a choice obstructed by greens.
&nbsp;
Without allies, the SNP, although dominant in Holyrood, the Scottish Parliament, with 63 seats out of 129, found itself in a minority and tried without success new partners. Both the conservative and Labour opposition had presented a motion of distrust, one against Humza Yousaf personally and the other against his entire government. This week it should have been voted and the Scottish Greens had indicated that they would vote against the Prime Minister, leaving Humza Yousaf few hopes to save himself. Parliament now has 28 days to find a new prime minister and Humza Yousaf said it will remain in office until the successor is appointed.
&nbsp;
He is the youngest leader in the leadership of the SNP, Humza Yousaf, praised for his communication skills capable of joining the party, so he was unable to turn on and close the Sturgeon era. Its thirteen months in power, in the midst of the carrovi crisis, were marked mainly by the clashes with London, for example on a Scottish law on gender change, finally blocked by the British Government, and on the UK's position in the conflict between Israel and Hamas in Gaza, or also on the authorization of a large oil project in the North Sea.
&nbsp;
Also on the judicial front was a particularly difficult year for the SNP: an investigation targeted the party's finances, and Sturgeon himself was questioned by the police, and her husband, Peter Murrell, former party CEO, accused of undue appropriation. A few months after the legislative elections, the Independents are also threatened by Labour, rising to Scotland.
&nbsp;
His struggle for Scottish self-determination, moreover, ended in a dead end since, at the end of 2022, the British Supreme Court ruled that only the British government can authorize a new referendum. The last vote, in 2014, was won by the "no" with 55%. In the British political system, the Scottish Government has jurisdiction over many sectors, such as education, health, justice and the environment, while the British Government maintains defence and diplomatic relations.

