AGI - &nbsp; Spanish premier Pedro Sanchez remains at the head of the executive >: he remains at the Moncloa "with more force if possible" despite "the discredit campaign" of which he accuses the right opposition; but calls for "a reflection" on the polarization of politics in Spain to prevent "disinformation or political debate". This closes, at least for now, the pause period that had taken place on Wednesday, after the opening of a <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-24/indagata-moglie-sanchez-evaluation-dimissions-26158186/"> judicial survey</a> on the work of his wife.
&nbsp;
Negating that he acted as "political calculus", Sanchez made the announcement with a solemn speech of nine minutes > pronounced on the stairway of the Moncloa Palace, the headquarters of the presidency of the Spanish government, where the premier has an apartment and where he had been locked up these days, with his wife and two daughters. A few minutes before he went to the palace of La Zarzuela to communicate to the king his decision. Then he made it known to the country: "I have decided to continue with even more force in the leadership of the Spanish government," he said, underlining that his decision "represents a firm point" and will allow him to resume working "untilfully, firmly", for the expectation of regeneration, progress and consolidation of rights and freedoms. For Sanchez, Spain "since the mud colonizes uncleanly" political life, contaminating "with unimaginable toxic practices" comparison. "My wife and I know that this defamatory campaign will not stop. We have been suffering for ten years"; but there is only one way to reverse the situation and it is that the social majority "as it has done in these five days mobilize in a firm commitment to dignity and good sense, putting an end to the policy of shame that we have been suffering for too long".
&nbsp;
Sanchez had closed himself in silence after the announcement, last Wednesday, by a Madrid court, of the opening of a preliminary investigation for "traffic of influences" and "corruption" against his wife, Begona Gomez>. With a shock announcement, he wrote a four-page letter to the Spanish in which he explained that he was considering the possibility of resigning to protect his family. And, absolutely unprecedented, Sanchez has suspended all its public activities, in fact 'closing' the government. Closed to Moncloa, practically without contact with the outside, for five days the premier confronted his wife limiting itself to responding laconicly to messages from the outside, and doing gymnastics. However, there has been social mobilization. At the cry of "Pedro, stay!", thousands of supporters gathered on Saturday in front of the Socialist Party headquarters in Madrid to ask him not to leave his place.
<h2> The charges charged by Begona Gomez</h2>
The investigation against Pedro Sanchez's wife, placed under the investigative secret, was opened after a complaint of the association "Manos limpias>", which is collective near the extreme right. In particular, according to an online media El Confidencial, also linked to right-wing environments, the links established by Begona Gomez with the Globalia group, sponsor of the foundation in which he worked, when Air Europa, a global airline company, treated with the Sanchez government to obtain public aid. The company received, in November 2020, 475 million euros, from a 10 billion fund intended to support the strategic enterprises in difficulty because of the pandemic. But even dozens of others benefited from aid, including several of its competitors (Iberia, Vueling, Volotea). And on Thursday the public prosecutor asked for the archiving of the investigation, while Manos Limpias admitted that his complaint was based solely on press articles (the judge in charge of the case still has to clarify his intentions).
&nbsp;
According to Sanchez, the complaint is the umpteenth stage of the destabilization campaign carried out against him by "a coalition of interests of the right and extreme right" which "does not accept the verdict of the ballot". From his arrival to power, six years ago, the legitimacy of the socialist leader has always been questioned from the right and the extreme right, which never forgave him of being brought to power by the extreme left and the political parties Basque and Catalan, thanks to a vote of distrust against his predecessor, the Conservative Mariano Rajoy, overwhelmed by a scandal of corruption.
&nbsp;
The political context has become even more tense in recent months, when Pedro Sanchez, who finished second in the July 23rd elections behind his rival, the leader of the People's Party, Alberto Nunez Feijoo>, managed to return to power thanks to the support of independent parties in exchange for an amnesty law for separatists involved in the attempt to secessate Catalonia in 2017. The law was passed at first reading by the Members in March and should be finally adopted at the end of May. Now we wait for the answer of the right that from Wednesday we are making jokes of Sanchez, accusing him of wanting to shoot himself by victim. "A head of government can't give a show like a teenager and everyone runs behind him, begging him not to leave and not to get angry," said Feijoo.&nbsp;

